* Logical line = portion of a long line that fits on a single screen row.<3;1>
* BOF = Beginning of file.<4;1>
* EOF = End of file just after last character or newline.<5;1>
* BOL = Beginning of line, which can be BOF.<6;1>
* EOL = End of line at a newline or EOF if no terminating newline.<7;1>
* TOP = Top of page.<8;1>
* BOP = Bottom of page.<11;1>
### Terminal Dimensions<13;1>
Historical serial CRT terminals were 80 columns by 24 rows.  Later serial terminals were 80x25 to make room for a status line.  X Windows, Windows, and Mac systems have terminal emulators (typically `xterm`, `ansi`, or `vt100`) that can be<16;1>
resized on the fly.  Typically the column width is a multiple of eight (8) to account for `TAB` stops.  The terminal dimensions can be found with `stty -a` or check the `TERM` definition (see `/usr/share/misc/terminfo`) or both.<20;1>
Curses library supports the environment variables `TERM`, `LINES`, and `COLUMNS`.  It possible to temporarily set `LINES` or `COLUMNS` or both smaller than the<22;1>
terminal window size for easier testing and debugging, eg.<24;5>
$ LINES=10 ./ae file<2;1>
